The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 29, 2004 				 Linc Pen scripts 77% rise in net
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, April 28: Linc Pen and Plastics has posted a whopping 77 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 3.85 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 2.18 crore in the previous year. Turnover increased to Rs 85.29 crore against Rs 63.30 crore in 2002-03, a rise of 35 per cent.																								Improved capacity utilisation which resulted in better operational efficiency were the prime reasons behind this good financial and operating performance, said managing director Deepak Jalan.																								According to Jalan, Linc Pen topped the industry growth rate, which was around 10-15 per cent, by initiating aggressive sales and marketing strategies.																								The companys focus for the next two to three years is to primarily increase the market share in the ballpoint and gelpen segment. Linc Pens hopes to cross the Rs 100-crore mark in the current fiscal and plans to introduce at least four new products. 																								Exports rose to Rs 10.18 crore during 2003-04 against Rs 7.84 crore in the previous year. Currently, exports make up 12 per cent of the total turnover of the company and is expected to grow to 25 per cent over the next two years.
